    <body>
    <h1>rawdog-md</h1>
    <h3>This is a <a href="https://handlebarsjs.com/">Handlebars</a> Page</h3>
    <p>The purpose of this Handlebars page is to generate an HTML file with Handlebars that consumes contexts created from the <code>pages</code> directory. 
    <br> This is useful for creating a separate page, like a Home page that contains a list of blog posts like this:</p>

    <h5>List of Markdown Posts</h5>
    <ul>
    {{#withSortByDate $pages "date" "desc"}}
        {{#withFilter this "$type" "markdown"}}
            {{#each this}}
                {{#with this}}
                <li>
                    <a href="{{$url}}">{{title}}</a><span style="font-size: 11px;"> • {{date}}</span>
                </li>
                {{/with}}
            {{/each}}
        {{/withFilter}}
    {{/withSortByDate}}
    </ul>

    <p>Contexts are special variables that are available in all Handlebars files, including those in the templates directory and the <code>pages</code> directory.</p>

    <h3>Default Contexts Provided by rawdog-md™</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>$url:</strong> The URL of the current page</li>
        <li><strong>$type:</strong> The type of the current page. It can be <code>Markdown</code>, <code>Handlebars</code>, or <code>HTML</code></li>
        <li><strong>$filename:</strong> The filename of the current page without the extension</li>
        <li><strong>$body:</strong> The body of the current page. 
            <ul>
                <li>If the current page is a Markdown, it will be the rendered HTML content of the Markdown file.</li>
                <li>If the current page is an HTML file, it will be the exact HTML content.</li>
                <li>If the current page is a Handlebars file, it won't be rendered at all, since under the hood, it will be treated as a template.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>$pages:</strong> An array of contexts for each page in the pages directory
            <ul>
                <li><code>$pages[index].$url:</code> The URL of the page</li>
                <li><code>$pages[index].$type:</code> The type of the page</li>
                <li><code>$pages[index].$filename:</code> The filename of the page without the extension</li>
                <li><code>$pages[index].$body:</code> The body of the page</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <p>Note that default contexts start with <code>$</code> to avoid conflicts with user-defined contexts. However, you can override it if you really want to by using the same name with the <code>$</code> prefix.</p>

    <h3>Raw HTML</h3>
    <p>If you don't need contexts or dynamic content, you can use raw HTML content in the Handlebars file. It will be rendered as is.</p>
    <p>This is useful for things like 'Not Found' page, where you don't need any dynamic content.</p>
    <p>Go to <a href="not_found.html">Not Found</a> page example</p>
